  "output": "## Performance Analysis — jobsquare\n\nContext check first: this is a **Python** codebase (async fetchers → SQLite store → CLI/agent), not a JS/React app — there's no frontend here, so \"React re-renders\" doesn't apply. I've substituted the equivalent Python-world category (redundant object churn) where relevant. Findings below are ranked by actual impact given the scale: 114 configured ATS sources (`sources.yaml`), several of which (`amazon`, `microsoft`, `netflix`) explicitly page through **thousands** of roles per run on a 12h schedule.\n\n---\n\n### 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:55-74` (`Store.diff`)\n\nThis is the clearest N+1 in the codebase. For every job returned by a fetch run (potentially thousands), it does a separate `SELECT`, then a separate `INSERT`/`UPDATE`, each as its own round-trip through the sqlite3 driver:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    for job in jobs:\n        row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n        if row is None:\n            new.append(job)\n            self._insert(cur, job, now)          # separate INSERT per row\n        else:\n            ...\n            self._update(cur, job, now)           # separate UPDATE per row\n```\n\nFor a run with, say, 3,000 jobs across Amazon/Microsoft/Netflix, that's 3,000+ discrete `cur.execute()` calls in a Python loop — each with sqlite3's per-statement parsing/binding overhead.\n\n**Fix — batch the lookup, batch the writes:**\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    existing = {}\n    # SQLite caps host params (~999-32766); chunk if job counts can exceed that\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 900):\n        chunk = keys[i:i + 900]\n        placeholders = \",\".join(\"?\" * len(chunk))\n        rows = self.conn.execute(\n            f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({placeholders})\", chunk)\n        existing.update({r[\"key\"]: r[\"content_hash\"] for r in rows})\n\n    new, changed, to_touch, to_insert, to_update = [], [], [], [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        prev_hash = existing.get(job.key)\n        if prev_hash is None:\n            new.append(job)\n            to_insert.append({**job.to_row(), \"now\": now})\n        elif prev_hash != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job)\n            to_update.append({**job.to_row(), \"now\": now})\n        else:\n            to_touch.append((now, job.key))\n\n    if to_insert:\n        self.conn.executemany(\"\"\"INSERT INTO jobs (...) VALUES (:key, ...)\"\"\", to_insert)\n    if to_update:\n        self.conn.executemany(\"\"\"UPDATE jobs SET ... WHERE key=:key\"\"\", to_update)\n    if to_touch:\n        self.conn.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", to_touch)\n\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nThis turns O(N) round trips into O(N/900) reads plus 3 bulk `executemany` calls — the standard fix for row-by-row diffing against a DB.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Redundant computation — `filters.py:11-41` (regex recompiled per job)\n\n`match()` is called once per job by `filter_jobs`'s list comprehension, and it calls `_compile(exclude)` / `_compile(include)` **on every single call**:\n\n```python\ndef match(job: Job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...) -> bool:\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):   # recompiled every job\n            return False\n    if include:\n        if not any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(include)):  # recompiled every job\n            return False\n```\n\n`_compile` runs `re.compile` for every keyword, for every job. With N jobs and K keywords, that's O(N·K) `re.compile` calls instead of O(K) — `re.compile` is meaningfully more expensive than a match against an already-compiled pattern, and the keyword lists (`include`/`exclude`/`locations`) are invariant across the whole filter pass.\n\n**Fix — compile once, pass compiled patterns down:**\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = None\n    max_age = rules.get(\"max_age_days\")\n    if max_age:\n        cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=float(max_age))\n\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    locations = rules.get(\"locations\")\n\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude,\n                                      locations=locations, cutoff=cutoff)]\n\n\ndef match(job: Job, *, include: list[re.Pattern] | None = None,\n          exclude: list[re.Pattern] | None = None, ...) -> bool:\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    ...\n```\n\nPython's `re` module does cache the last ~512 compiled patterns internally, but that cache is evicted under load from *other* regex use in the same process (e.g. all the `re.search` calls in `fetchers.py`'s Google/D.E.Shaw/Two Sigma parsers), so it's not a reliable substitute for compiling once explicitly.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Redundant computation — `models.py:66-75` (`content_hash` recomputed twice per changed job)\n\n`Job.content_hash` is a plain `@property`, not cached. In the (now-fixed) `Store.diff` path, it gets computed once for the comparison and then a second time inside `to_row()` for the `UPDATE`/`INSERT` payload — a SHA-256 over the same string, twice, per changed/new job:\n\n```python\n@property\ndef content_hash(self) -> str:\n    blob = \"|\".join((self.title, self.location, self.url, self.department))\n    return hashlib.sha256(blob.encode(\"utf-8\")).hexdigest()[:16]\n```\n\nThis is cheap in isolation, but it's pure waste since `Job` fields don't change after construction. Since `Job` is `@dataclass(slots=True)`, `functools.cached_property` won't work directly (no `__dict__`), but you can add an explicit cache slot:\n\n```python\n@dataclass(slots=True)\nclass Job:\n    ...\n    _content_hash: str | None = field(default=None, repr=False, compare=False)\n\n    @property\n    def content_hash(self) -> str:\n        if self._content_hash is None:\n            blob = \"|\".join((self.title, self.location, self.url, self.department))\n            self._content_hash = hashlib.sha256(blob.encode(\"utf-8\")).hexdigest()[:16]\n        return self._content_hash\n```\n\nLow priority relative to #1/#2, but free once you're already touching `Store.diff`.\n\n---\n\n### 4. Caching opportunity — `fetchers.py` pagination loops re-derive `seen` sets but don't cache across sources/runs\n\nEach paginated fetcher (`fetch_google`, `fetch_twosigma`, `fetch_optiver`, `fetch_microsoft`, `fetch_netflix`, `fetch_amazon`) rebuilds a `seen: set[str]` from scratch and re-fetches the *entire* board every run, even though `store.py` already tracks `first_seen`/`last_seen` per job. There's no conditional-request support (`If-Modified-Since`/`ETag`) even though `httpx` supports it natively and several of these APIs (Greenhouse, Lever, Ashby) return standard HTTP caching headers.\n\n**Suggestion:** for the JSON-API sources that support it, thread through `If-None-Match`/`If-Modified-Since` headers using the previous run's response headers (stored in `meta` via `Store.set_meta`/`get_meta`, which already exists for the scan watermark). On a `304`, skip parsing entirely. This won't help the bespoke scrape-only sources (Google, D.E. Shaw, Two Sigma) since those don't expose caching headers, but it would cut work meaningfully for the ~9 clean-JSON-API sources this repo already normalizes.\n\nThis isn't free — worth doing if fetch latency/rate-limiting from these 114 sources every 12h is a concern; otherwise it's optional.\n\n---\n\n### 5. Memory leaks — none found\n\n- `httpx.AsyncClient` in `fetch_all` (`fetchers.py:770-787`) is created and closed in a `try/finally`, and is reused across all 114 concurrent fetches (correct — avoids per-source client/connection-pool churn).\n- Both `Store` construction sites (`pipeline.py:42`, `agent.py:55`) go through `with Store(...) as store:`, so the sqlite3 connection is always closed.\n- The `seen: set[str]` accumulators in fetchers are function-local and bounded by `max_pages`, so they don't persist or grow across runs.\n\nNo action needed here.\n\n---\n\n### Priority order\n1. **`Store.diff` N+1 → batched IN + executemany** (`store.py`) — highest impact, scales directly with job count × 2x/day schedule.\n2. **Regex recompilation in `filter_jobs`** (`filters.py`) — cheap fix, O(N·K) → O(K).\n3. **`content_hash` double-hash** (`models.py`) — trivial, bundle with #1 since you're editing `Store.diff` anyway.\n4. **Conditional HTTP requests for JSON-API fetchers** — optional, only worth it if fetch time/rate-limits become a problem.\n",
